peptide adduct\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lysine oligomer precursor\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 on iron-sulfur phases gives formate as an early fixed-carbon product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Supported by iron-sulfur vent carbon-fixation concepts and mineral-catalyzed CO2 reduction pathways central to hydrothermal prebiotic chemistry; this provides upstream feedstock rather than a lysine-specific step (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Barge et al., 2019; Kitadai et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 hydrogenation to formaldehyde equivalents\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-470K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor serpentinization-linked reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type and related reduction chemistry furnishes reduced one-carbon organics represented here by formaldehyde as a transferable carbonyl feedstock.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a literature-grounded hydrothermal feedstock-generating step based on magnetite/Fe-driven CO2 reduction and serpentinization chemistry, included to connect hydrothermal and surface inventories; it is a generalized systems-chemistry bridge rather than a lysine-demonstrated reaction (Amend & Shock, 1998; Barge et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential mineral-mediated carbon fixation and carbon-carbon bond formation generate alpha-keto acid products represented by pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included because alpha-keto acids are central hydrothermal hubs and because iron-sulfur chemistry is known to support reductive amination of simple alpha-keto acids. It is not a lysine route per se, but a realistic hydrothermal precursor node linking environments (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Barge et al., 2019; Kitadai et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface spark-discharge generation of HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borosilicate silicate surface\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and borosilicate surface effects\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"electric discharge in CH4/NH3/N2-like atmospheres; strong UV-compatible surface setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Energetic atmospheric/surface processing yields cyanide-bearing products that accumulate in surface waters.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is a core prebiotic hub. Spark-discharge experiments establish rich amino/nitrile product inventories, and the only tentative lysine report appears in borosilicate reactors with strong silicate surface effects (Miller, 1953; Ring et al., 1972; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011; Criado-Reyes et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN hydration to formamide under UV-active surface conditions\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalysis with clay concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, wet-dry surface cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical hydration and rearrangement of cyanide-bearing mixtures generates formamide-rich residues.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide-mediated photochemistry is a standard surface branch from HCN-rich chemistry and is included as a literature-consistent surface feedstock pathway rather than a direct lysine route; the research report notes UV photochemistry produces complex amino-acid inventories but not confirmed lysine (Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002; Nuevo et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to aminoacetonitrile-containing polymers\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay concentration and/or UV-active mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN-rich pools, oligomerization followed by hydrolysis-prone polymer formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide oligomerization yields aminonitrile-bearing oligomers and aminoacetonitrile as a key monomeric motif.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminoacetonitrile-derived polymers are the basis of the historical but unconfirmed lysine claim from HCN polymer hydrolysis; modern reassessment confirms only simpler amino acids and related products, not lysine. This reaction is therefore necessary but explicitly non-diagnostic for lysine (Moser & Matthews, 1968; Cleaves, 2010; Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanide-derived chain extension to acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide-assisted cyanosulfidic conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, anoxic evaporitic pool chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanosulfidic homologation of simple carbonyl/cyanide feedstocks generates C3 nitriles represented by acrylonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research identifies acrylonitrile as a plausible C3 building block accessible from HCN chemistry and relevant to lysine problem framing. This step is a connected abstraction of Sutherland-type nitrile homologation chemistry, though not a demonstrated lysine-forming route (Patel et al., 2015; Thoma & Powner, 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonia addition to acrylonitrile to beta-aminopropionaldehyde precursor pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide-mineral assisted, clay-concentrated\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanide/ammonia-rich aqueous surface pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic ammonia addition and partial hydrolysis/reduction of nitrile functionality generate beta-aminopropionaldehyde-type intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report specifically names beta-aminopropionaldehyde as an informative intermediate accessible from acrylonitrile plus ammonia. However, Patel et al. note that further homologation tends to cyclize, obstructing linear lysine precursor formation; this reaction is therefore a gateway to the identified bottleneck (Patel et al., 2015; Thoma & Powner, 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Attempted cyanosulfidic homologation to 5-aminopentanal bottleneck\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide-driven photoredox with borate stabilization of carbonyl intermediates\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; homologation competes with cyclization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive nitrile/aldehyde homologation could in principle furnish the Strecker precursor 5-aminopentanal, but cyclization strongly competes and usually dominates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is included because the literature identifies 5-aminopentanal as the aldehyde required for a Strecker route to lysine while also stating there is no known prebiotic source and that cyanosulfidic chain extension beyond beta-aminopropionaldehyde is unlikely due to cyclization toward proline-like products. This step is therefore explicitly speculative and low-confidence but required to represent the documented bottleneck (Miller & Van Trump, 1981; Patel et al., 2015; Thoma & Powner, 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Prebiotic access to diaminopropionic acid from dehydroalanine nitrile chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate-buffered surface pool with clay concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonia addition gives high-yield Dpr under mild prebiotic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia adds to dehydroalanine nitrile-type precursor pools to furnish diaminopropionic acid after hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is one of the strongest literature-supported diamino-acid syntheses relevant to lysine surrogacy. Thoma & Powner showed diaminopropionic acid can be formed prebiotically in high yield and can serve as a functional lysine surrogate, though not as lysine itself (Thoma & Powner, 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge and meteoritic-accessible formation of diaminobutyric acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borosilicate silicate surface\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"spark-discharge with silicate surface effects\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic electric discharge or analogous energetic processing\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Energetic nitrile-rich chemistry forms shorter-chain diamino acids, including C4 homologues, after hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Shorter diamino acids are firmly established prebiotic products and delineate the chain-length barrier to lysine. Diaminobutyric acid has been detected in spark-discharge contexts and related extraterrestrial inventories, unlike lysine (Ring et al., 1972; Wolman et al., 1972; Meierhenrich et al., 2004; Thoma & Powner, 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Borosilicate-catalyzed spark-discharge tentative lysine formation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borosilicate silicate surface\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borosilicate reactor surface; silicate/boron leaching effects\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"CH4/NH3/N2 spark discharge; lysine tentatively assigned by GC-MS after derivatization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex spark-discharge network over silicate surfaces produces a broad amino-acid inventory in which lysine was tentatively detected.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the only published experimental report of lysine under plausibly prebiotic laboratory conditions, but the identification remains tentative and not yet independently confirmed. It must therefore be the central direct lysine-access reaction in any literature-faithful network (Criado-Reyes et al., 2021; Thoma & Powner, 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-irradiated ice photochemistry to diaminohexanoic acid isomers\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"12 K irradiation followed by warming to 300K-equivalent residue analysis\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low to 1 atm upon residue recovery\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photochemistry with mineral collection/stabilization on warming\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"H2O:CH3OH:NH3:CO:CO2 ice irradiation; strong UV\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photolysis of astrophysical ice analogues yields complex residues containing diaminohexanoic acid isomers but not confirmed lysine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report specifically notes formation of two diaminohexanoic acids sharing lysine's formula but with different regiochemistry, showing that C6 diamino backbones are accessible while 2,6-diaminohexanoic acid remains elusive (Munoz Caro et al., 2002; Nuevo et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hypothetical isomer-resolution or rearrangement from diaminohexanoic acid isomers to lysine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable, 300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal cycling, mineral-interface selection; no direct experimental demonstration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Conceptual regioisomer selection or rearrangement within a complex residue pool could enrich the lysine constitutional isomer from C6 diamino-acid mixtures.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is explicitly speculative and included only to connect the literature-observed diaminohexanoic acid isomers to the lysine target. No direct prebiotic rearrangement to lysine has been demonstrated; the research instead emphasizes the unresolved regiochemical barrier (Munoz Caro et al., 2002; Nuevo et al., 2008; Thoma & Powner, 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker-type lysine synthesis from 5-aminopentanal bottleneck precursor\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis sequence; no known prebiotic source of precursor aldehyde\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Canonical Strecker addition to 5-aminopentanal would generate the alpha-amino center and, after hydrolysis, lysine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This route is included because the literature explicitly states that Strecker chemistry would require 5-aminopentanal, but this aldehyde lacks any known prebiotic source and the mechanism does not independently explain the epsilon-amino group. It is therefore a theoretical dead-end rather than an established route (Miller & Van Trump, 1981; Thoma & Powner, 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Montmorillonite-mediated lysine capture and oligomer-compatible concentration\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling on clay-rich pools; selective adsorption/intercalation of cationic amino acids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"If lysine is available, clay intercalation and concentration favor retention and subsequent oligomerization-compatible organization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature shows montmorillonite strongly and selectively concentrates lysine through interlayer cation exchange, and lysine displays favorable peptide/depsipeptide coupling behavior once present. This is not a synthesis step but a realistic downstream selection node linking rare lysine formation to biochemical utility (Cuadros et al., 2009; Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2019; Thoma & Powner, 2023).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct borosilicate spark route\",\n      \"description\": \"The only direct literature-reported lysine access: reduced carbon feeds atmospheric/surface cyanide chemistry, and borosilicate-assisted spark discharge tentatively yields lysine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN polymer branch to tentative lysine\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN oligomerization generates aminoacetonitrile-rich polymer chemistry historically claimed to produce lysine on hydrolysis, but modern reanalysis does not confirm it; the branch is retained as a literature-defined false-positive pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Acrylonitrile homologation bottleneck to Strecker lysine\",\n      \"description\": \"A cyanide-derived C3 nitrile is aminated and homologated toward 5-aminopentanal, then enters a formal Strecker lysine step; this pathway is explicitly bottlenecked by cyclization and missing precursor evidence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface carbon feed into direct spark lysine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction supplies formaldehyde-like reduced carbon that migrates to surface environments and participates in the only tentative lysine-forming spark network.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-supported reduced-carbon route to spark lysine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal alpha-keto acid production is treated as a systems-level reduced-carbon reservoir feeding surface atmospheric chemistry and tentative lysine formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"UV ice diaminohexanoic isomer route\",\n      \"description\": \"UV photolysis of ice analogues yields diaminohexanoic acid isomers; a speculative biochemical selection/rearrangement step is required to reach lysine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Alternative UV isomer branch to lysine\",\n      \"description\": \"A second diaminohexanoic acid isomer produced in UV residues is conceptually connected to lysine through the same unresolved regioisomer-selection barrier.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-photochemical branch feeding spark-discharge lysine inventory\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN hydration to formamide is included as a connected UV-active branch of surface nitrile chemistry that can recycle into broader amino-acid-producing residue networks culminating in tentative lysine detection.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Short diamino acid surrogate pathway from dehydroalanine nitrile\",\n      \"description\": \"This route does not produce lysine directly but reaches diaminopropionic acid, the best-supported prebiotic lysine surrogate, highlighting replacement chemistry when lysine is absent.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Short homolog boundary pathway through diaminobutyric acid\",\n      \"description\": \"Formation of C4 diamino acid demonstrates that diamino-acid chemistry exists prebiotically but stalls before lysine; if rare lysine appears elsewhere, the same biochemical concentration machinery can capture it.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_019\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Lysine", "overall_strategy": "This network is literature-constrained and represents a systems-chemistry map to lysine as an unresolved, low-confidence prebiotic target rather than a validated robust synthesis. The design therefore connects (i) hydrothermal carbon fixation to shared feedstocks such as formate, formaldehyde, pyruvate, and ammonia; (ii) surface HCN/cyanosulfidic and spark-discharge chemistries that generate shorter diamino-acid surrogates, nitriles, aldehydes, and tentative C6 diamino products; and (iii) biochemical/prebiotic selection and concentration processes that can capture, preserve, or assemble lysine only if it is supplied by rare surface-generated routes. Ten distinct pathways are included, but most terminate in bottlenecks, surrogate products, or tentative lysine access points exactly because the literature indicates that lysine formation is largely unsolved. The network uses convergent hubs (HCN, formaldehyde, pyruvate, acrylonitrile, 5-aminopentanal) and explicitly marks speculative bridging steps where the research identifies gaps.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", 