": "mol_014", "formula": "C6H14N2O2", "iupac_name": "2,6-diaminohexanoic acid", "common_name": "lysine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H14N2O2/c7-4-2-1-3-5(8)6(9)10/h5H,1-4,7-8H2,(H,9,10)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C6H14N2O2", "iupac_name": "diaminohexanoic acid isomer", "common_name": "diaminohexanoic acid isomer", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C6H14N2O2", "iupac_name": "diaminohexanoic acid isomer", "common_name": "diaminohexanoic acid isomer 2", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C3H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacrylic acid nitrile precursor family", "common_name": "dehydroalanine nitrile precursor", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C6H13N3O2", "iupac_name": "lysine-containing depsipeptide or peptide adduct", "common_name": "lysine oligomer precursor", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 on iron-sulfur phases gives formate as an early fixed-carbon product.", "reasoning": "Supported by iron-sulfur vent carbon-fixation concepts and mineral-catalyzed CO2 reduction pathways central to hydrothermal prebiotic chemistry; this provides upstream feedstock rather than a lysine-specific step (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Barge et al., 2019; Kitadai et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 hydrogenation to formaldehyde equivalents", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-470K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor serpentinization-linked reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Fischer-Tropsch-type and related reduction chemistry furnishes reduced one-carbon organics represented here by formaldehyde as a transferable carbonyl feedstock.", "reasoning": "This is a literature-grounded hydrothermal feedstock-generating step based on magnetite/Fe-driven CO2 reduction and serpentinization chemistry, included to connect hydrothermal and surface inventories; it is a generalized systems-chemistry bridge rather than a lysine-demonstrated reaction (Amend & Shock, 1998; Barge et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Sequential mineral-mediated carbon fixation and carbon-carbon bond formation generate alpha-keto acid products represented by pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Included because alpha-keto acids are central hydrothermal hubs and because iron-sulfur chemistry is known to support reductive amination of simple alpha-keto acids. It is not a lysine route per se, but a realistic hydrothermal precursor node linking environments (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Barge et al., 2019; Kitadai et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface spark-discharge generation of HCN", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borosilicate silicate surface"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and borosilicate surface effects", "aqueous": "true", "other": "electric discharge in CH4/NH3/N2-like atmospheres; strong UV-compatible surface setting"}, "mechanism": "Energetic atmospheric/surface processing yields cyanide-bearing products that accumulate in surface waters.", "reasoning": "HCN is a core prebiotic hub. Spark-discharge experiments establish rich amino/nitrile product inventories, and the only tentative lysine report appears in borosilicate reactors with strong silicate surface effects (Miller, 1953; Ring et al., 1972; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011; Criado-Reyes et al., 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "HCN hydration to formamide under UV-active surface conditions", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalysis with clay concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, wet-dry surface cycling"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical hydration and rearrangement of cyanide-bearing mixtures generates formamide-rich residues.", "reasoning": "Formamide-mediated photochemistry is a standard surface branch from HCN-rich chemistry and is included as a literature-consistent surface feedstock pathway rather than a direct lysine route; the research report notes UV photochemistry produces complex amino-acid inventories but not confirmed lysine (Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002; Nuevo et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "HCN oligomerization to aminoacetonitrile-containing polymers", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay concentration and/or UV-active mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN-rich pools, oligomerization followed by hydrolysis-prone polymer formation"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide oligomerization yields aminonitrile-bearing oligomers and aminoacetonitrile as a key monomeric motif.", "reasoning": "Aminoacetonitrile-derived polymers are the basis of the historical but unconfirmed lysine claim from HCN polymer hydrolysis; modern reassessment confirms only simpler amino acids and related products, not lysine. This reaction is therefore necessary but explicitly non-diagnostic for lysine (Moser & Matthews, 1968; Cleaves, 2010; Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cyanide-derived chain extension to acrylonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide-assisted cyanosulfidic conditions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, anoxic evaporitic pool chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Cyanosulfidic homologation of simple carbonyl/cyanide feedstocks generates C3 nitriles represented by acrylonitrile.", "reasoning": "The deep research identifies acrylonitrile as a plausible C3 building block accessible from HCN chemistry and relevant to lysine problem framing. This step is a connected abstraction of Sutherland-type nitrile homologation chemistry, though not a demonstrated lysine-forming route (Patel et al., 2015; Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Ammonia addition to acrylonitrile to beta-aminopropionaldehyde precursor pool", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide-mineral assisted, clay-concentrated", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanide/ammonia-rich aqueous surface pool"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic ammonia addition and partial hydrolysis/reduction of nitrile functionality generate beta-aminopropionaldehyde-type intermediates.", "reasoning": "The research report specifically names beta-aminopropionaldehyde as an informative intermediate accessible from acrylonitrile plus ammonia. However, Patel et al. note that further homologation tends to cyclize, obstructing linear lysine precursor formation; this reaction is therefore a gateway to the identified bottleneck (Patel et al., 2015; Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Attempted cyanosulfidic homologation to 5-aminopentanal bottleneck", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide-driven photoredox with borate stabilization of carbonyl intermediates", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; homologation competes with cyclization"}, "mechanism": "Successive nitrile/aldehyde homologation could in principle furnish the Strecker precursor 5-aminopentanal, but cyclization strongly competes and usually dominates.", "reasoning": "This is included because the literature identifies 5-aminopentanal as the aldehyde required for a Strecker route to lysine while also stating there is no known prebiotic source and that cyanosulfidic chain extension beyond beta-aminopropionaldehyde is unlikely due to cyclization toward proline-like products. This step is therefore explicitly speculative and low-confidence but required to represent the documented bottleneck (Miller & Van Trump, 1981; Patel et al., 2015; Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Prebiotic access to diaminopropionic acid from dehydroalanine nitrile chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate-buffered surface pool with clay concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ammonia addition gives high-yield Dpr under mild prebiotic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia adds to dehydroalanine nitrile-type precursor pools to furnish diaminopropionic acid after hydrolysis.", "reasoning": "This is one of the strongest literature-supported diamino-acid syntheses relevant to lysine surrogacy. Thoma & Powner showed diaminopropionic acid can be formed prebiotically in high yield and can serve as a functional lysine surrogate, though not as lysine itself (Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Spark-discharge and meteoritic-accessible formation of diaminobutyric acid", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_003", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borosilicate silicate surface"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "spark-discharge with silicate surface effects", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic electric discharge or analogous energetic processing"}, "mechanism": "Energetic nitrile-rich chemistry forms shorter-chain diamino acids, including C4 homologues, after hydrolysis.", "reasoning": "Shorter diamino acids are firmly established prebiotic products and delineate the chain-length barrier to lysine. Diaminobutyric acid has been detected in spark-discharge contexts and related extraterrestrial inventories, unlike lysine (Ring et al., 1972; Wolman et al., 1972; Meierhenrich et al., 2004; Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Borosilicate-catalyzed spark-discharge tentative lysine formation", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_003", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borosilicate silicate surface", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borosilicate reactor surface; silicate/boron leaching effects", "aqueous": "true", "other": "CH4/NH3/N2 spark discharge; lysine tentatively assigned by GC-MS after derivatization"}, "mechanism": "Complex spark-discharge network over silicate surfaces produces a broad amino-acid inventory in which lysine was tentatively detected.", "reasoning": "This is the only published experimental report of lysine under plausibly prebiotic laboratory conditions, but the identification remains tentative and not yet independently confirmed. It must therefore be the central direct lysine-access reaction in any literature-faithful network (Criado-Reyes et al., 2021; Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "UV-irradiated ice photochemistry to diaminohexanoic acid isomers", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_001", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "12 K irradiation followed by warming to 300K-equivalent residue analysis", "pressure": "low to 1 atm upon residue recovery", "catalyst": "UV photochemistry with mineral collection/stabilization on warming", "aqueous": "false", "other": "H2O:CH3OH:NH3:CO:CO2 ice irradiation; strong UV"}, "mechanism": "Photolysis of astrophysical ice analogues yields complex residues containing diaminohexanoic acid isomers but not confirmed lysine.", "reasoning": "The report specifically notes formation of two diaminohexanoic acids sharing lysine's formula but with different regiochemistry, showing that C6 diamino backbones are accessible while 2,6-diaminohexanoic acid remains elusive (Munoz Caro et al., 2002; Nuevo et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Hypothetical isomer-resolution or rearrangement from diaminohexanoic acid isomers to lysine", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable, 300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "geothermal cycling, mineral-interface selection; no direct experimental demonstration"}, "mechanism": "Conceptual regioisomer selection or rearrangement within a complex residue pool could enrich the lysine constitutional isomer from C6 diamino-acid mixtures.", "reasoning": "This step is explicitly speculative and included only to connect the literature-observed diaminohexanoic acid isomers to the lysine target. No direct prebiotic rearrangement to lysine has been demonstrated; the research instead emphasizes the unresolved regiochemical barrier (Munoz Caro et al., 2002; Nuevo et al., 2008; Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Strecker-type lysine synthesis from 5-aminopentanal bottleneck precursor", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis sequence; no known prebiotic source of precursor aldehyde"}, "mechanism": "Canonical Strecker addition to 5-aminopentanal would generate the alpha-amino center and, after hydrolysis, lysine.", "reasoning": "This route is included because the literature explicitly states that Strecker chemistry would require 5-aminopentanal, but this aldehyde lacks any known prebiotic source and the mechanism does not independently explain the epsilon-amino group. It is therefore a theoretical dead-end rather than an established route (Miller & Van Trump, 1981; Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Montmorillonite-mediated lysine capture and oligomer-compatible concentration", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycling on clay-rich pools; selective adsorption/intercalation of cationic amino acids"}, "mechanism": "If lysine is available, clay intercalation and concentration favor retention and subsequent oligomerization-compatible organization.", "reasoning": "The literature shows montmorillonite strongly and selectively concentrates lysine through interlayer cation exchange, and lysine displays favorable peptide/depsipeptide coupling behavior once present. This is not a synthesis step but a realistic downstream selection node linking rare lysine formation to biochemical utility (Cuadros et al., 2009; Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2019; Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Direct borosilicate spark route", "description": "The only direct literature-reported lysine access: reduced carbon feeds atmospheric/surface cyanide chemistry, and borosilicate-assisted spark discharge tentatively yields lysine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_004"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "HCN polymer branch to tentative lysine", "description": "HCN oligomerization generates aminoacetonitrile-rich polymer chemistry historically claimed to produce lysine on hydrolysis, but modern reanalysis does not confirm it; the branch is retained as a literature-defined false-positive pathway.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_008"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Acrylonitrile homologation bottleneck to Strecker lysine", "description": "A cyanide-derived C3 nitrile is aminated and homologated toward 5-aminopentanal, then enters a formal Strecker lysine step; this pathway is explicitly bottlenecked by cyclization and missing precursor evidence.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_015"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface carbon feed into direct spark lysine", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction supplies formaldehyde-like reduced carbon that migrates to surface environments and participates in the only tentative lysine-forming spark network.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_005", "mol_004"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Pyruvate-supported reduced-carbon route to spark lysine", "description": "Hydrothermal alpha-keto acid production is treated as a systems-level reduced-carbon reservoir feeding surface atmospheric chemistry and tentative lysine formation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_004"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "UV ice diaminohexanoic isomer route", "description": "UV photolysis of ice analogues yields diaminohexanoic acid isomers; a speculative biochemical selection/rearrangement step is required to reach lysine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Alternative UV isomer branch to lysine", "description": "A second diaminohexanoic acid isomer produced in UV residues is conceptually connected to lysine through the same unresolved regioisomer-selection barrier.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Formamide-photochemical branch feeding spark-discharge lysine inventory", "description": "HCN hydration to formamide is included as a connected UV-active branch of surface nitrile chemistry that can recycle into broader amino-acid-producing residue networks culminating in tentative lysine detection.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Short diamino acid surrogate pathway from dehydroalanine nitrile", "description": "This route does not produce lysine directly but reaches diaminopropionic acid, the best-supported prebiotic lysine surrogate, highlighting replacement chemistry when lysine is absent.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Short homolog boundary pathway through diaminobutyric acid", "description": "Formation of C4 diamino acid demonstrates that diamino-acid chemistry exists prebiotically but stalls before lysine; if rare lysine appears elsewhere, the same biochemical concentration machinery can capture it.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_019"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_011"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_004", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_012", "rxn_015"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_005", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_015"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_012", "rxn_014", "rxn_015"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_016"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 118017.29798316956, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T15:39:46.224009", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Lysine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network is literature-constrained and represents a systems-chemistry map to lysine as an unresolved, low-confidence prebiotic target rather than a validated robust synthesis. The design therefore connects (i) hydrothermal carbon fixation to shared feedstocks such as formate, formaldehyde, pyruvate, and ammonia; (ii) surface HCN/cyanosulfidic and spark-discharge chemistries that generate shorter diamino-acid surrogates, nitriles, aldehydes, and tentative C6 diamino products; and (iii) biochemical/prebiotic selection and concentration processes that can capture, preserve, or assemble lysine only if it is supplied by rare surface-generated routes. Ten distinct pathways are included, but most terminate in bottlenecks, surrogate products, or tentative lysine access points exactly because the literature indicates that lysine formation is largely unsolved. The network uses convergent hubs (HCN, formaldehyde, pyruvate, acrylonitrile, 5-aminopentanal) and explicitly marks speculative bridging steps where the research identifies gaps.\n\nMOLECULES (19 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_004: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: CHO2- (formate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C3H4O3 (pyruvate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C2H4N2 (aminoacetonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C3H3N (acrylonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C3H7NO (beta-aminopropionaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C5H11NO (5-aminopentanal) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C4H8N2O2 (diaminopropionic acid) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C4H10N2O2 (diaminobutyric acid) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C6H14N2O2 (lysine) [target]\n  - mol_015: C6H14N2O2 (diaminohexanoic acid isomer) [intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C6H14N2O2 (diaminohexanoic acid isomer 2) [intermediate]\n  - mol_017: CH3NO (formamide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_018: C3H5NO2 (dehydroalanine nitrile precursor) [intermediate]\n  - mol_019: C6H13N3O2 (lysine oligomer precursor) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (16 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_006 (Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_005 (Hydrothermal CO2 hydrogenation to formaldehyde equivalents) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_001, mol_002, mol_006 -> mol_007 (Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_003, mol_005 -> mol_004 (Surface spark-discharge generation of HCN) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_004 -> mol_017 (HCN hydration to formamide under UV-active surface conditions) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_004, mol_003 -> mol_008 (HCN oligomerization to aminoacetonitrile-containing polymers) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_004, mol_005 -> mol_009 (Cyanide-derived chain extension to acrylonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_009, mol_003 -> mol_010 (Ammonia addition to acrylonitrile to beta-aminopropionaldehyde precursor pool) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_010, mol_004, mol_005 -> mol_011 (Attempted cyanosulfidic homologation to 5-aminopentanal bottleneck) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_018, mol_003 -> mol_012 (Prebiotic access to diaminopropionic acid from dehydroalanine nitrile chemistry) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_004, mol_003, mol_005 -> mol_013 (Spark-discharge and meteoritic-accessible formation of diaminobutyric acid) [Surface]\n  - rxn_012: mol_004, mol_003, mol_005 -> mol_014 (Borosilicate-catalyzed spark-discharge tentative lysine formation) [Surface]\n  - rxn_013: mol_003, mol_001, mol_005 -> mol_015, mol_016 (UV-irradiated ice photochemistry to diaminohexanoic acid isomers) [Surface]\n  - rxn_014: mol_015 -> mol_014 (Hypothetical isomer-resolution or rearrangement from diaminohexanoic acid isomers to lysine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_015: mol_011, mol_004, mol_003 -> mol_014 (Strecker-type lysine synthesis from 5-aminopentanal bottleneck precursor) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_016: mol_014 -> mol_019 (Montmorillonite-mediated lysine capture and oligomer-compatible concentration) [Biochemical]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Direct borosilicate spark route (3 steps)\n  - P2: HCN polymer branch to tentative lysine (3 steps)\n  - P3: Acrylonitrile homologation bottleneck to Strecker lysine (5 steps)\n  - P4: Hydrothermal-to-surface carbon feed into direct spark lysine (4 steps)\n  - P5: Pyruvate-supported reduced-carbon route to spark lysine (3 steps)\n  - P6: UV ice diaminohexanoic isomer route (2 steps)\n  - P7: Alternative UV isomer branch to lysine (2 steps)\n  - P8: Formamide-photochemical branch feeding spark-discharge lysine inventory (3 steps)\n  - P9: Short diamino acid surrogate pathway from dehydroalanine nitrile (2 steps)\n  - P10: Short homolog boundary pathway through diaminobutyric acid (2 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_004, mol_005, mol_007, mol_009, mol_011\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 4\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of lysine remains one of origin-of-life chemistry's hardest unsolved problems\n\n**Lysine has never been reliably synthesized under prebiotic conditions**, making it one of the most conspicuously absent proteinogenic amino acids from the abiotic chemical inventory. Across seven decades of spark discharge experiments, meteorite analyses, hydrothermal simulations, UV photolysis studies, and HCN polymerization reactions, lysine appears in at most one or two tentative detections\u2014none confirmed by modern high-resolution techniques until a single 2021 borosilicate-catalyzed experiment. This gap matters because lysine's \u03b5-amino group provides irreplaceable cationic functionality for nucleic acid binding, enzyme catalysis, and protein structure. The consensus view treats lysine as a **\"biological invention\"**\u2014an amino acid that entered the genetic code only after enzymatic biosynthetic pathways evolved, not one drawn from the prebiotic environment (Thoma & Powner, *JACS*, 2023).\n\n---\n\n## The structural challenge: a 6-carbon diamine defeats standard prebiotic mechanisms\n\nLysine (2,6-diaminohexanoic acid) possesses two features that collectively make prebiotic synthesis extraordinarily difficult: a **6-carbon backbone** and **two amino groups** separated by four methylene units. Every major prebiotic amino acid synthesis mechanism fails at one or both of these requirements.\n\n**The Strecker synthesis**, the dominant route to \u03b1-amino acids in prebiotic chemistry, converts an aldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 into an \u03b1-aminonitrile, then an \u03b1-amino acid. For lysine, the required starting aldehyde would be **5-aminopentanal** (H\u2082N\u2013(CH\u2082)\u2084\u2013CHO). This molecule is itself complex with no known prebiotic source, and the Strecker mechanism can only generate the \u03b1-amino group\u2014it cannot explain the \u03b5-amino group's origin. The Strecker route is thus a theoretical dead-end for lysine (Miller & Van Trump, 1981, *Origin of Life*, Springer).\n\n**Cyanosulfidic chemistry** (the Powner\u2013Sutherland pathways) achieves remarkable selectivity in producing precursors for ~12 proteinogenic amino acids from HCN, H\u2082S, phosphate, and UV light (Patel et al., *Nature Chemistry*, 2015, 7:301\u2013307). However, Patel et al. explicitly noted that **cyclization events during homologation of \u03b2-aminopropionaldehyde make further chain extension to the acyclic Strecker precursor of lysine \"appear unlikely.\"** The pathway defaults to proline (cyclic C5) instead of achieving the linear C6 diamine chain.\n\n**HCN polymerization** offers the only historical claim of lysine detection from truly prebiotic chemistry. Moser & Matthews (*Experientia*, 1968, 24:658\u2013659) reported \"small amounts of lysine\" from hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile-derived polymers. However, Cleaves's high-resolution LC-MS re-examination (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2010, 40:587) confirmed only glycine, serine, alanine, and N-carbamyl-2,3-diaminosuccinic acid from HCN oligomer hydrolysis\u2014**lysine was not among confirmed products**. Ruiz-Bermejo et al. (*Life*, 2013, 3:421) reviewed all HCN polymerization experiments and found that while 12 of 20 protein amino acids have been detected across various conditions, lysine's inclusion is based solely on the unconfirmed 1968 report.\n\n---\n\n## Experimental evidence: one tentative detection across decades of work\n\n### Miller-Urey experiments consistently fail to produce lysine\n\nThe original Miller experiment (1953, *Science*, 117:528\u2013529) detected five amino acids; lysine was absent. Ring et al. (*PNAS*, 1972, 69:765\u2013768) expanded the inventory to ~20 amino acids using CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O/NH\u2083 discharge\u2014still no lysine. Johnson et al.'s reanalysis of Miller's archived volcanic apparatus samples using modern LC-FD/ToF-MS (*Science*, 2008, 322:404) found **22 amino acids and 5 amines**\u2014lysine absent. Parker et al.'s reanalysis of Miller's 1958 H\u2082S experiment (*PNAS*, 2011, 108:5526\u20135531) identified 23 amino acids including 7 organosulfur compounds\u2014again, no lysine.\n\n**The sole exception** is Criado-Reyes et al. (*Scientific Reports*, 2021, 11:21009), who conducted spark discharge experiments comparing **borosilicate glass** and **Teflon** reactors using CH\u2084/NH\u2083/N\u2082 mixtures. They detected **56 organic products** by GC-MS after TMS derivatization, including lysine (compound #14), identified with a NIST library similarity index \u226598%. Total amino acid yields were dramatically higher in borosilicate (**159 \u00b5g/mg crude** buffered at pH 8.7) versus Teflon (**27 \u00b5g/mg**). The authors attributed this to silicate surface catalysis leaching boron and silicon species into solution. This remains the **only published report of lysine detection in a Miller-Urey-type experiment**, though the identification is described as \"tentatively assigned\" and no specific quantitative yield for lysine alone was reported in the main text.\n\n### Lysine is absent from all analyzed meteorites\n\nLysine has not been detected in the Murchison meteorite or any other carbonaceous chondrite. This absence is so consistent that it serves as a **contamination diagnostic**: Engel & Macko (*Precambrian Research*, 2001) and Glavin et al. (*Meteoritics & Planetary Science*, 2020) both noted that the absence of lysine, histidine, arginine, tyrosine, and phenylalanine confirms that detected amino acids are indigenous rather than terrestrial contaminants. However, shorter-chain diamino acids **have** been found: Meierhenrich et al. (*PNAS*, 2004, 101:9182\u20139186) identified DL-2,3-diaminopropanoic acid and DL-2,4-diaminobutanoic acid at parts-per-billion concentrations in Murchison\u2014both racemic, confirming abiotic origin. The pattern is clear: **diamino acid abundance drops sharply with carbon chain length**, and the C6 lysine falls below detection limits.\n\n### UV photolysis produces isomers but not lysine itself\n\nMu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (*Nature*, 2002) irradiated H\u2082O:CH\u2083OH:NH\u2083:CO:CO\u2082 ices at 12 K with UV light and detected 16 amino acids\u2014plus, notably, **\"two diaminohexanoic acids\"** with the same molecular formula as lysine but different structural arrangements. Lysine itself was not confirmed. Nuevo et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2008) reported a chromatographic peak at lysine's retention time in UV-irradiated ice residues, but co-injection experiments revealed it was **likely ethanolamine (NH\u2082CH\u2082CH\u2082OH)** coeluting with lysine. The authors concluded: \"the presence of lysine in our residues cannot be totally ruled out\" but remained unconfirmed.\n\n---\n\n## Key intermediates and the carbon chain elongation bottleneck\n\nThe chemical path from simple prebiotic molecules (HCN, NH\u2083, H\u2082CO, H\u2082O) to lysine requires solving two nested problems: building a linear C6 chain and installing amino groups at both termini.\n\n**Potential precursor molecules** include aminoacetonitrile (H\u2082NCH\u2082CN, which oligomerizes to HCN polymers), acrylonitrile (CH\u2082=CHCN, a C3 building block accessible from HCN chemistry), \u03b2-aminopropionaldehyde (from acrylonitrile + NH\u2083), and various \u03b1-keto acids. In modern biochemistry, lysine arises through either the **diaminopimelate (DAP) pathway** starting from aspartate semialdehyde + pyruvate (bacteria, plants; 7\u201310 enzymatic steps), or the **\u03b1-aminoadipate (AAA) pathway** starting from \u03b1-ketoglutarate + acetyl-CoA (fungi; ~8 enzymatic steps). Neither pathway has any demonstrated prebiotic equivalent\u2014both require sophisticated enzymatic catalysis with no known abiotic substitutes.\n\nThe shorter diamino acids **\u03b1,\u03b3-diaminobutyric acid** (C4) and **\u03b1,\u03b2-diaminopropionic acid** (C3) have been detected in spark discharge experiments (Ring et al., 1972; Wolman et al., 1972) and meteorites (Meierhenrich et al., 2004). These are lysine's shorter homologues, demonstrating that the chemistry for diamino acid formation exists prebiotically\u2014but only for chains up to C4\u2013C5. The yield of diamino acids drops precipitously with each additional carbon, and the **C6 threshold has never been crossed** in confirmed prebiotic synthesis.\n\nA particularly informative intermediate is **diaminopropionic acid (Dpr)**, which Thoma & Powner (*JACS*, 2023, 145:3121\u20133130) showed can be synthesized prebiotically by ammonia addition to dehydroalanine nitrile with **81\u201385% yield**. Dpr can serve as a functional lysine surrogate in peptide catalysis, though its lower sidechain pKa (~6.3 vs. lysine's ~10.8) limits its functional equivalence.\n\n---\n\n## Environmental conditions and thermodynamic barriers paint a harsh picture\n\n**Thermodynamic calculations** by Amend & Shock (*Science*, 1998, 281:1659\u20131662) showed that amino acid synthesis from CO\u2082, NH\u2084\u207a, and H\u2082 is endergonic under surface seawater conditions (18\u00b0C, 1 atm) for all 20 amino acids, but becomes exergonic for 11 amino acids at hydrothermal conditions (100\u00b0C, 250 bar). The \"late\" amino acids, including lysine, have mean Gibbs free energies of formation of **~285 \u00b1 94 kJ/mol** at the surface\u2014significantly higher than the ~169 \u00b1 42 kJ/mol for the 10 \"early\" amino acids. Higgs & Pudritz (*Astrobiology*, 2009, 9:483\u2013490) demonstrated that prebiotic amino acid abundance correlates strongly (**r = 0.96**) with free energy of formation, and lysine sits at the thermodynamically unfavorable extreme.\n\n**Hydrothermal environments** present a double-edged sword. While moderate-temperature alkaline vents (Lost City type, 40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311) provide thermodynamically favorable conditions for amino acid synthesis, amino acids also decompose rapidly at elevated temperatures. Bada, Miller & Zhao (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 1995, 25:111\u2013118) showed that amino acids are **irreversibly destroyed above ~240\u00b0C**, ruling out black smoker environments. Lysine's \u03b5-amino group provides an additional decomposition pathway through lactam formation and cross-linking reactions, making it **more thermally labile** than simpler amino acids. Sato et al. (*Industrial & Engineering Chemistry Research*, 2004, 43:3217\u20133222) demonstrated that amino acid degradation rates increase with functional group complexity at 200\u2013340\u00b0C.\n\n**Wet-dry cycling** in evaporitic pools at 65\u201385\u00b0C promotes peptide bond formation but has not been shown to synthesize lysine de novo. Intriguingly, Frenkel-Pinter et al. (*PNAS*, 2019, 116:16338) found that proteinogenic basic amino acids (Lys, Arg, His) **preferentially polymerize** into linear depsipeptides compared to their non-proteinogenic analogues, and the resulting oligomers enhance RNA duplex thermal stability. This suggests lysine has superior polymerization properties once available\u2014but does not solve the prior synthesis problem.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts concentrate lysine but cannot yet create it\n\n**Montmorillonite clay** shows remarkable selectivity for lysine. A 2024 study in *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta* demonstrated that cationic amino acids (lysine, arginine) are **selectively adsorbed** with Langmuir constants far exceeding those of neutral amino acids at pH 5\u20137 in NaCl solution. Lysine's protonated \u03b5-amino group drives cation exchange into montmorillonite's interlayer space, increasing d-spacing from **1.2 to 2.1 nm** (Cuadros et al., *Colloids and Surfaces A*, 2009). Bezaly et al. (*Scientific Reports*, 2026) showed that lysine intercalation creates diverse nano-environments that may facilitate polymerization. However, Mg\u00b2\u207a competition reduces adsorption ~10-fold, and these interactions only concentrate pre-existing lysine\u2014they do not generate it.\n\n**Iron-sulfur minerals** catalyze reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to \u03b1-amino acids (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user; Barge et al., *PNAS*, 2019, 116:4828\u20134833), but only simple amino acids (alanine, glycine) have been produced. The reaction requires freshly precipitated FeS with strict metal specificity\u2014replacing FeS with other metal sulfides eliminates amino acid production (Kitadai et al., *Life*, 2018, 8:46). Pyrite photocatalysis can produce amino acids with **14.5\u201342.4% enantiomeric excess** for D-amino acids (*Nature Communications*, 2024), but no iron-sulfur system has produced lysine or any C6 diamino acid.\n\n**Borosilicate glass** (silicate minerals) may represent the most promising catalytic avenue, given the Criado-Reyes et al. (2021) result. Their experiment yielded **~6\u00d7 more amino acids** in borosilicate versus Teflon reactors, with some amino acids forming exclusively in the presence of silicate surfaces. A follow-up study by Jenewein & Garc\u00eda-Ruiz (conference abstract, *Macla*, 2025) extends this work to pure quartz versus borosilicate systems, with a manuscript reportedly under review at *PNAS*.\n\n---\n\n## Lysine occupies a unique evolutionary and chemical niche\n\n**Genetic code chronology** places lysine as a **mid-to-late addition**, ranking approximately 10th in Trifonov's consensus temporal order (*Gene*, 2000, 261:139\u2013151): G/A \u2192 V/D \u2192 P \u2192 S \u2192 E/L \u2192 T \u2192 R \u2192 N \u2192 **K** \u2192 Q \u2192 I \u2192 C \u2192 H \u2192 F \u2192 M \u2192 Y \u2192 W. Makarov et al. (*JACS*, 2023, 145:3840\u20133850) showed the early amino acid alphabet **completely lacked positively charged residues**\u2014Lys, Arg, and His were all absent, with metal ion cofactors likely compensating for the missing positive charges in primitive proteins.\n\nThe existence of **two completely independent biosynthetic pathways** for lysine (DAP and AAA)\u2014sharing no homologous enzymes in their later steps\u2014represents remarkable convergent evolution and underscores the intense selective pressure for this amino acid (Fondi et al., *BMC Evolutionary Biology*, 2007, 7(Suppl 2):S3). The biosynthetic cost of lysine (~30 ATP equivalents) is among the highest of any amino acid, reflecting the thermodynamic difficulty that also blocks prebiotic synthesis.\n\nThoma & Powner's 2023 work provides a compelling **chemical rationale for lysine's selection**. In direct competition experiments, lysine thioacids underwent peptide coupling with aminonitriles in **96% yield** at pH 7, while ornithine (C5 homologue) and diaminobutyric acid (C4 homologue) cyclized to lactams at **>90% yield**, completely blocking peptide formation. Only lysine's four-methylene spacer is long enough to prevent intramolecular cyclization while maintaining an electronically isolated, fully protonated sidechain amine (pKa ~10.8). This creates an extraordinarily sharp chemical selection: among all possible \u03c9-amino-\u03b1-amino acids, **only lysine is compatible with peptide chain elongation**.\n\n---\n\n## What remains unsolved and why it matters\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of lysine remains fundamentally unresolved. The core bottleneck is **carbon chain elongation to C6 with regioselective \u03b5-amination**\u2014no known prebiotic mechanism achieves this. The cyclization barrier identified by Sutherland's group means that standard HCN homologation chemistry defaults to cyclic products (proline) rather than linear C6 diamine chains. Extraterrestrial delivery offers no solution, as lysine has not been detected in any meteorite.\n\nSeveral paths forward deserve investigation. The borosilicate-catalyzed spark discharge result (Criado-Reyes et al., 2021) suggests that **mineral surface catalysis** may enable more complex amino acid synthesis than solution-phase chemistry alone\u2014but this remains a single, tentative detection requiring independent confirmation. Computational reaction network exploration (Wo\u0142os et al.; RTIP methods in *JACS Au*, 2024) has not yet been applied to lysine, representing a significant frontier. The possibility of **multi-step, systems-chemistry approaches** combining different prebiotic environments (hydrothermal synthesis \u2192 mineral concentration \u2192 wet-dry polymerization) remains largely unexplored for lysine specifically.\n\nThe field faces a paradox: lysine is chemically the **optimal amino acid for peptide chain elongation** and functionally essential for nucleic acid binding, yet it appears to be among the last amino acids biology could access. Whether this means early life operated without positive charges (using metal ions instead), employed simpler surrogates like diaminopropionic acid, or accessed lysine through yet-undiscovered prebiotic chemistry remains one of origin-of-life research's most consequential open questions.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nLysine's prebiotic absence is not simply a gap in our knowledge\u2014it is a **structurally informative constraint** on origin-of-life scenarios. The thermodynamic cost (\u0394G ~285 kJ/mol at surface conditions), the Strecker synthesis dead-end, the cyclization barrier in cyanosulfidic chemistry, and the blank across meteorite inventories collectively point to a genuine chemical boundary. The Criado-Reyes et al. (2021) borosilicate result and the diaminohexanoic acid isomers in UV ice experiments (Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002) suggest the boundary is not absolute\u2014C6 diamino compounds can form abiotically under specific conditions\u2014but the particular regiochemistry of 2,6-diaminohexanoic acid remains elusive. The most productive research directions likely involve mineral-catalyzed spark or photochemistry, systematic exploration of HCN polymer hydrolysis products with modern mass spectrometry, and computational pathway discovery. Until a robust prebiotic route to lysine is found, origin-of-life models must account for how early biology functioned without\u2014or eventually invented\u2014one of its most indispensable building blocks.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"ta