lysis literature explicitly in reasoning for this branch.\",\n        \"Do not imply this branch is lysine-productive; keep it explicitly as a bottleneck/failure branch.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.5,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.32,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.18,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.72\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.37,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.39,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.57,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.24,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.35,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway correctly centers the homologation bottleneck highlighted in the literature, but the chemistry is too speculative to support a viable route. Acrylonitrile is a plausible C3 nitrile intermediate, but its direct conversion with ammonia to beta-aminopropionaldehyde is not well represented, and chain extension from that intermediate to 5-aminopentanal is especially unsupported. The pathway usefully encodes the problem, not a credible solution.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_008\",\n        \"rxn_009\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Represent nitrile-first intermediates more faithfully, e.g., beta-aminopropionitrile rather than the aldehyde equivalent.\",\n        \"Mark rxn_009 as highly speculative and unsupported by current experiments.\",\n        \"If retained, separate the bottleneck branch from the direct lysine-producing branch to avoid overstating continuity.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.5,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.32,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.18\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.28,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.52,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.49,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.08,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.29,\n      \"feedback\": \"As a theoretical Strecker endpoint branch, this pathway 