opionaldehyde, and 5-aminopentanal is highly speculative and correctly reflects a bottleneck, but should be marked more explicitly as unresolved rather than quasi-productive. The sole actual lysine-producing step is appropriately tentative and aligns with Criado-Reyes et al. 2021, which is a major strength. Likewise, the inclusion of diaminohexanoic acid isomers and shorter diamino acids matches literature showing near-misses and homologues rather than robust lysine synthesis.\\n\\nLiterature alignment is generally good at the conceptual level: the network captures lysine as an unresolved target, the Strecker dead-end, the HCN polymerization ambiguity, the unique borosilicate spark exception, the UV isomer near-miss, and the use of shorter diamino acids as surrogates. However, because the supplied network summary does not show reaction-level citations or detailed mineral agent assignments, it falls short of the strictest literature-constrained standard. Several surface reactions also do not explicitly list required mineral agents in the provided summary, which violates the original synthesis-network specification even if the intended chemistry is literature-aware.\\n\\nOverall, this is an acceptable evaluative network for mapping the chemical boundary around lysine, but it is not an approved high-confidence synthesis network to lysine. It is best viewed as a well-structured negative-result network with one tentative production branch and several literature-faithful bottleneck branches.\",\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.83,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.74\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_003": 0.45, "rxn_010": 0.72}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.58, "pathway_coherence": 0.68, "environmental_progression": 0.7, "target_achievement": 0.74, "overall_confidence": 0.67, "feedback": "This is the strongest direct-to-target pathway because it mirrors the only literature-supported tentative lysine detection: spark discharge in