ves as an inventory branch leading toward the literature-reported diaminohexanoic-acid isomer near-miss rather than a direct lysine route (Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002; Nuevo et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Aminoacetonitrile formation from HCN-rich surface inventory", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borosilicate glass / silicate surface"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "silicate and clay surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN-rich evaporitic or discharge-processed pool"}, "mechanism": "Condensation within nitrile-rich inventory gives aminonitrile species, here represented by aminoacetonitrile as an HCN polymerization/feedstock hub.", "reasoning": "Aminoacetonitrile is a well-recognized aminonitrile in prebiotic chemistry and historically central to HCN polymerization claims. This node is used to represent the literature-supported aminonitrile hub without overstating its conversion to lysine (Moser & Matthews, 1968; Cleaves, 2010; Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "HCN polymerization and hydrolysis branch to diaminopropionic acid surrogate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay and sulfide-assisted cyanosulfidic milieu", "aqueous": "true", "other": "followed conceptually by hydrolysis; surrogate branch"}, "mechanism": "Aminonitrile-rich networks can yield short-chain diamino acid products/surrogates upon oligomerization and hydrolysis.", "reasoning": "This branch is included because shorter diamino acids are demonstrably more accessible than lysine. It is partly literature-based and partly a network-connecting abstraction: historical HCN polymer hydrolysis does not confirm lysine, while Thoma & Powner strongly support prebiotic access to diaminopropionic-acid-type functionality via nitrile chemistry. This reaction should be interpreted as a surrogate branch, not a lysine-producing step (Cleaves, 2010; Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2013; Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cyanosulfidic / nitrile homologation branch to acrylonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide mineral mediated UV-active surface chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN/H2S/UV-type cyanosulfidic setting"}, "mechanism": "HCN-derived surface chemistry can furnish small nitrile building blocks, here represented by acrylonitrile as a C3 nitrile precursor.", "reasoning": "Acrylonitrile is discussed in the literature as a plausible C3 building block accessible from HCN chemistry. This node is used specifically to encode the carbon-chain elongation problem on the way toward lysine, not as a validated productive route (Patel et al., 2015; Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Ammonia addition to acrylonitrile gives beta-aminopropionaldehyde inventory", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide/clay mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic; represented as literature-noted bottleneck precursor generation"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia incorporation into C3 nitrile-derived inventory provides beta-aminopropionaldehyde-type species relevant to homologation discussions.", "reasoning": "The research report specifically identifies beta-aminopropionaldehyde as a key intermediate discussed in relation to lysine failure. This step is retained only to encode that literature bottleneck and is explicitly low-confidence as a clean prebiotic conversion. It should be treated as a problem-defining branch rather than a robust synthesis (Patel et al., 2015; Thoma & Powner, 2023, speculative connector)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Problematic homologation to 5-aminopentanal", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate/clay surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "homologation attempt; cyclization competes strongly"}, "mechanism": "Formal chain extension toward the required C5 aminoaldehyde precursor is attempted but chemically disfavored because cyclization diverts the system.", "reasoning": "This reaction is intentionally included as an unresolved dead-end because the literature explicitly states that homologation beyond beta-aminopropionaldehyde toward the acyclic lysine precursor appears unlikely due to cyclization. This is not a validated route and must be read as a mapped failure point (Patel et al., 2015; Miller & Van Trump, 1981; Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Theoretical Strecker-type conversion of 5-aminopentanal to lysine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borosilicate glass / silicate surface", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "silicate/clay surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "theoretical Strecker framework; precursor not known prebiotically"}, "mechanism": "If 5-aminopentanal were available, Strecker chemistry could in principle install the alpha-amino acid center to produce lysine.", "reasoning": "The literature explicitly identifies this as a theoretical dead-end because 5-aminopentanal has no known prebiotic source. This step is therefore included only to represent the mechanistic reason standard Strecker synthesis fails for lysine, not as an experimentally supported route (Miller & Van Trump, 1981; Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "UV ice photochemistry to diaminohexanoic acid isomers", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "12 K ice photolysis followed by warming to 300K for residue analysis", "pressure": "low during irradiation / 1 atm upon recovery", "catalyst": "mineral surfaces used here as concentrators for terrestrial analog mapping", "aqueous": "false", "other": "UV irradiation of H2O:CH3OH:NH3:CO:CO2-type ice analogs; near-miss branch"}, "mechanism": "Photoprocessed nitrogen/carbonyl-rich ice residues yield C6 diamino acid isomeric products sharing lysine's molecular formula but not its confirmed regiochemistry.", "reasoning": "Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. reported two diaminohexanoic acids in UV-irradiated ice residues, while Nuevo et al. found lysine remained unconfirmed because a peak likely corresponded to ethanolamine. This branch is therefore a literature-supported near-miss, not a lysine synthesis (Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002; Nuevo et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Borosilicate-enhanced spark-discharge tentative lysine formation", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borosilicate glass / silicate surface", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "spark discharge, bulk aqueous collection near ambient; buffered analysis at pH 8.7", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borosilicate glass", "aqueous": "true", "other": "CH4/NH3/N2 discharge system; lysine tentatively assigned by GC-MS/TMS derivatization"}, "mechanism": "Energetic discharge over silicate-reactor surfaces produces complex amino-acid inventories; lysine appears as a tentative minor product in borosilicate systems.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest direct lysine-access branch because it reflects the only published tentative lysine detection in a prebiotic experiment. The step is intentionally represented as an inventory-level formation event rather than a resolved mechanism, because the underlying chemistry remains unknown and requires independent confirmation (Criado-Reyes et al., 2021; Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Surface production of shorter diamino acid homologue (diaminobutyric acid)", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borosilicate glass / silicate surface"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "silicate/clay surfaces in discharge or hydrolysis-derived inventory", "aqueous": "true", "other": "comparative homologue branch"}, "mechanism": "Shorter-chain diamino acid formation occurs more readily than C6 lysine in abiotic nitrile/ammonia networks.", "reasoning": "Shorter diamino acids such as diaminobutyric acid are documented in abiotic contexts and help define the chain-length cutoff below lysine. This branch is included to reflect the literature pattern that diamino chemistry is prebiotically accessible only up to shorter homologues (Ring et al., 1972; Wolman et al., 1972; Meierhenrich et al., 2004; Thoma & Powner, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Biochemical/prebiotic concentration and selection of trace lysine on montmorillonite", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["montmorillonite-rich mineral interface", null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite adsorption/intercalation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 5-7, saline pool, concentration rather than synthesis"}, "mechanism": "If lysine is formed even at trace level, cation-exchange adsorption and interlayer partitioning on montmorillonite selectively retain and concentrate it for downstream chemistry.", "reasoning": "Montmorillonite does not create lysine, but recent adsorption studies show strong selective concentration of lysine due to its cationic sidechain. This biochemical-stage reaction captures the plausible retention/selection of rare lysine once formed, which is one of the few literature-supported advantages available to lysine in prebiotic systems (Cuadros et al., 2009; Cuadros et al., 2024; Bezaly et al., 2026; Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2019)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Direct borosilicate spark-discharge lysine branch", "description": "The only literature-supported tentative direct lysine formation route: surface discharge chemistry in borosilicate systems produces a complex amino-acid inventory that includes tentatively assigned lysine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface C1 feed into tentative borosilicate lysine formation", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced carbon is delivered as formate, transformed into surface carbonyl inventory, then participates in the only tentative lysine-producing borosilicate discharge branch.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Theoretical Strecker dead-end via 5-aminopentanal", "description": "A literature-defined impossibility branch: if 5-aminopentanal existed, Strecker chemistry could yield lysine, but that precursor has no known prebiotic source.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal-fed homologation dead-end", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced carbon feeds surface carbonyl chemistry and then enters the same literature-recognized homologation 