entory and aminonitrile formation, culminating in diaminopropionic acid as a functional lysine surrogate rather than lysine itself.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Selection of rare lysine after tentative formation", "description": "Any trace lysine formed by the tentative borosilicate branch can be selectively concentrated on montmorillonite during biochemical/prebiotic stage processing.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_012", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_013"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_003", "mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_012"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_005", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_006", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_008", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": []}, {"molecule_id": "mol_013", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_014"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 114070.72925567627, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T15:45:32.806121", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Lysine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network is a literature-constrained map of the prebiotic lysine problem rather than a high-confidence productive synthesis. It centers the single tentative lysine-producing branch from borosilicate spark discharge, embeds the known near-miss and failure branches documented in the literature, and connects hydrothermal reduced-carbon generation to surface inventory formation and biochemical concentration/selection. Ten pathways are included, but most are explicitly low-confidence, dead-end, or surrogate routes because the literature shows no robust prebiotic synthesis of 2,6-diaminohexanoic acid. Hub molecules were chosen to reflect shared feedstocks and bottlenecks: CO2, NH3, HCN, aminoacetonitrile, and diaminohexanoic-acid isomers / lysine-adjacent C6 inventory.\n\nMOLECULES (15 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: NH3 (ammonia) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: CH2O2 (formic acid/formate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: H2CO (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: CHN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: CH3NO (formamide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C2H4N2 (aminoacetonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C3H3N (acrylonitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C3H7NO (beta-aminopropionaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C5H11NO (5-aminopentanal) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C6H12N2O2 (diaminohexanoic acid isomers) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C6H14N2O2 (lysine) [target]\n  - mol_014: C3H8N2O2 (diaminopropionic acid) [intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C4H10N2O2 (diaminobutyric acid) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (14 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_004 (Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001, mol_003 -> mol_005, mol_006 (Surface generation of